# Setup
 `coin ?= 0`
 ![The Bell Beneath](/assets/images/title.png)
 > by Vlad Raz
 > Check out the source on [GitHub](https://github.com/vladimir-o-razuvayev/odin_saga)
 + -> [Start the Game](#Start)

# Start
  `player_name ?= prompt("What is your name?") || "traveler"`
  `activate("/widgets/contacts.saga#Contacts")`
  > Rain taps against the shutters of the Hollow Bell inn, patient as fingers on a tabletop.
  > The room is registered to #{player_name}, though you do not remember signing the ledger.
  > The common room below has gone quiet in that late-afternoon way when everyone is listening to the weather and pretending not to.
  > `!visited_start` A sealed letter waits on your table. Its wax bears the mark of a crescent moon, pressed so deep the paper puckers around it.
  + *-> [Open the letter](#.Letter)
  + -> [Step into the village](#Village)

## Letter
  `visited_start := true`
  `map_known := true`
  `activate("/widgets/inventory.saga#Inventory")`
  ![Letter with crescent seal](/assets/images/letter.png)
  > The letter is brief: "#{player_name}, find the bell beneath the old watchtower before moonrise. Trust the woman with the blue scarf."
  > The ink looks fresh until you tilt the page, when it browns like something written years ago and only now remembered.
  > A charcoal map is sketched beneath the warning: village square, northern road, ruined tower, and one black circle where no road is drawn.
  + -> [Continue](#Village)

# Village
  `village_visits++`
  > The village of Brindlewick curls around a muddy square. Lanterns glow like fireflies in the rain, each one haloed in gold.
  > Roof gutters mutter into barrels. Somewhere a goat complains with the exhausted dignity of an old magistrate.
  > `map_known` The charcoal map from the letter is already soft at the creases, but the marked road seems darker than the rest no matter how often you fold it away.
  + -> [Visit the market square](/market.saga#Square)
  + `map_known` -> [Walk to the old watchtower road](#Road)
  + `!map_known` -> [Ask around for directions](#.Directions)
  + `coin >= 2` -> [Buy a dry cloak before leaving](/market.saga#Square.CloakSeller)
  + -> [Speak with the gate watch](#.GateWatch)

## Directions
  `map_known := true`
  `met_fishmonger := true`
  ![Fishmonger](/assets/images/fishmonger.png)
  > A fishmonger points with his pipe, drawing a wavering line through the rain as if sketching the road in smoke.
  > His stall smells of river mud, salt, and sharp green herbs packed around silver fish.
  >> [Fishmonger](/characters.saga#Fishmonger) Old road is north. Mind the stones. They listen.
  >> If a milestone turns its back on you, don't argue with it. Just thank it and keep walking.
  + -> [Continue](#Village)

## GateWatch
  `met_watchman := true`
  ![Watchman](/assets/images/watchman.png)
  > The watchman leans on his spear beneath the village arch, rain ticking from the brim of his iron cap.
  > His eyes move over you, the square, the road, and back again, measuring which of you is most likely to cause trouble.
  > `old_key` His eyes flick to the blackened key in your hand, then quickly away, as if the key has noticed him first.
  + -> [Ask about the watchtower](#.WatchtowerRumor)
  + -> [Return to the square](#Village)

### WatchtowerRumor
  `heard_bell_rumor := true`
  >> [Watchman](/characters.saga#Watchman) No bell there now. Not above ground, anyway.
  >> Folk used to say the tower rang for fog, fire, and weddings. Then one winter it rang all by itself for three nights.
  >> After that, people found reasons to build their houses facing south.
  + *-> [Press him for more](#..OldKey)
  + -> [Thank him and leave](#..)

### OldKey
  `old_key := true`
  > He slips a blackened key into your palm. It is heavier than it should be and leaves an oily crescent across your skin.
  >> [Watchman](/characters.saga#Watchman) If the lower door still stands, this might remember it.
  >> Don't force it. Old locks take offense, and some of them have long memories.
  + -> [Continue](#..)

# Road
  `road_steps++`
  > The northern road narrows between leaning birches. Their white trunks gleam like bones washed clean by rain.
  > Somewhere ahead, stone shifts against stone, patient and deliberate, though the air is perfectly still.
  > `has_cloak` Rain beads on your borrowed cloak and rolls away instead of finding your collar. For once, Brindlewick's weather fails to get what it wants.
  - `road_steps == 1` *-> [Continue](#.FirstSign)
  - `lantern_lit` -> [Continue](/ruins.saga#Gate)
  - -> [Continue](#.DarkRoad)

## FirstSign
  > A milestone turns as you pass it, revealing an arrow carved into its back.
  > Lichen flakes from the groove. The arrow points not down the road but slightly beneath it.
  + -> [Continue](#Road)

## DarkRoad
  > Without a lit lantern, the trees knit themselves into a wall of black needles.
  > The road remains under your boots, but every step sounds as if it lands in a room with a ceiling.
  + -> [Return to Brindlewick](#Village)
  + `heard_bell_rumor` -> [Try the road anyway](/ruins.saga#Gate)
